## 3. Infrastructure Issues and Limitations

### Why terminating SSL at the load balancer level is an issue
When SSL termination occurs at the load balancer level, the traffic is decrypted at the entry point. This means that the data traveling from the load balancer to the backend application servers (Servers 2 and 3) is transmitted in unencrypted plain text (HTTP) over the internal private network. If a malicious actor compromises the internal network layer, they can easily sniff all sensitive data.

### Why having only one MySQL server capable of accepting writes is an issue
Having only one MySQL server capable of accepting writes creates a clear performance bottleneck for database-heavy applications and remains a structural Single Point of Failure (SPOF). If Server 2 (Primary database) experiences a crash or hardware failure, the web infrastructure can no longer process write transactions (e.g., user registrations, updates, or purchases), rendering core application features broken.

### Why having servers with all the same components might be a problem
Bundling Nginx, the application server, and the MySQL database engine all together on the same underlying operating system causes severe resource contention. Each service actively competes for the exact same CPU, RAM, and Disk I/O resources. For example, if a heavy MySQL query consumes 100% of the available memory or CPU, it will starve Nginx and the application server, causing the entire server node to become unresponsive or crash. It also prevents independent horizontal scaling of individual components.
